<font color="#FF0000">WARRIORS-IN-CHARGE OF MEMORIES</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 18  6:02:57 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
All,<br><br>
Last year my younger daughter gave me the classic picture of the middle aged man (me) with his hand against The Wall and his head bowed. Gosts of his fallen comrades and himself look back out of the wall.<br><br>
I hung that picture so I would see it every say to remind myself to keep my head erect in pride and look back into The Wall and say &quot;I remember you, I love all of you, I am proud of you, and I will keep your memory alive!.<br><br>
I remember no names. Perhaps it is better that way. Only images in old photos and The Wall spark feelings that are understandable to only my Bro's. <br><br>
God, the Great Spirit, the Supreme Being, decided that we are the survivors for whatever reasons I am learning not to question. I guess we are the Warriors-in-Charge of Memories. Warriors can do that good, too! It hurts like hell at times, but it makes me feel real good that our Bro's are still with us in spirit as honored companions, and we still carry on the fight to keep their memories alive to the world. Warriors can do *that* good, too!<br><br>
Art, a Warrior-in-Charge of Memories<br><br>
but a really, really Dented Zippo, right now. OOPS, have to keep my head up!  <br><br>

